WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

2
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.600
LUCY: Life was given to
us a billion years ago.

3
00:01:43.700 --> 00:01:45.500
What have we done with it?

4
00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:05.500
Lucy. It's easy as pie.

5
00:02:05.600 --> 00:02:08.700
- In and out. all done and dusted.
- And why don't you do it yourself?

6
00:02:08.800 --> 00:02:12.600
The last thing the guy's expecting is a
total 10 turning up to deliver the case.

7
00:02:12.700 --> 00:02:15.600
- It'll blow his mind. Come on!
- What's in it?

8
00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:19.400
(CHUCKLING) Sweetheart!
Don't get paranoid on me. all right?

9
00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:21.100
You trust me. don't you?

10
00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:23.400
(UPBEAT DANCE MUSIC PLAYING)

11
00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:26.000
(ALL WHOOPING)

12
00:02:26.700 --> 00:02:27.900
Fuck!

13
00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:34.100
Richard. I really do like you. But...

14
00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:36.800
I have to take care of
myself right now. I gotta...

15
00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:40.100
I don't know. I've got to
concentrate on so many things.

16
00:02:40.200 --> 00:02:42.500
Hey. hey. What are you doing?

17
00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:44.900
I'm going home. because
I have exams on Monday.

18
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
I have to shower and I
have to study. okay?

19
00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:50.400
You know what? The other day.
I was in this museum.

20
00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:52.600
- And you know what I found out?
- What?

21
00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:55.000
The first ever woman was named Lucy.

22
00:02:59.900 --> 00:03:03.900
- Is that supposed to make me feel better?
- Yeah. No.

23
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.400
- I'll call you. Okay?
- Okay. okay. okay.

24
00:03:08.700 --> 00:03:11.100
I'll be honest with you.
I can't deliver the case myself.

25
00:03:11.200 --> 00:03:13.900
I had a little falling-out with the guy.
It's nothing major.

26
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
but if it's you. problem solved. You walk
in there. you go up to the reception.

27
00:03:19.100 --> 00:03:22.200
you ask for Mr. Jang to come down.
He comes down. he takes the case.

28
00:03:22.300 --> 00:03:25.300
you flash him your prettiest
smile and bounce.

29
00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:29.600
Look! You can even see
the reception from here.

30
00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:31.800
Come on.

31
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.000
- What's in the case?
- I don't know. it's just some paperwork.

32
00:03:35.100 --> 00:03:36.000
Yeah? Let's see it then.

33
00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:39.200
It's locked. And only
Mr. Jang has the code.

34
00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:41.300
- (SCOFFS)
- I'm just the delivery boy.

35
00:03:41.900 --> 00:03:44.300
- Do you get paid to do this?
- Yeah. kind of.

36
00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:46.200
Like how much?

37
00:03:46.900 --> 00:03:48.600
Okay! We are negotiating now or...

38
00:03:48.800 --> 00:03:51.300
No. no. How much do you get paid?
I want to know how much.

39
00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:53.600
A thousand dollars.

40
00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:57.500
You get paid a thousand dollars
for delivering paperwork? Really?

41
00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:00.400
I don't know. It takes me 10
minutes and they pay me a grand

42
00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:01.600
and the rest is none of my business.

43
00:04:01.700 --> 00:04:03.400
Well. it's none of my business either.
I'll tell you now.

44
00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:05.000
- Listen!
- What?

45
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
We split it down the middle. Hmm?

46
00:04:08.100 --> 00:04:10.700
(SIGHS)
That's 500 for you. and 500 for me.

47
00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:14.100
- Richard. I will call you.
- Listen. it's the third time this week.

48
00:04:14.200 --> 00:04:17.000
I'm showing up in the same hotel.
with the same cowboy hat.

49
00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:18.200
Oh.

50
00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:20.500
(IN SOUTHERN ACCENT) Problem solved!

51
00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:22.000
(IN NORMAL VOICE)
Go. go. I'll wait for you. Go.

52
00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:26.700
Lucy. honey... I've done this
a dozen times. It's paperwork.

53
00:04:26.800 --> 00:04:29.000
It's probably just some designs they
switched so they can copy them.

54
00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:32.700
That's how it works in this country.
Even my Stetson was made here. Look.

55
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.300
Says so on the label.
"Made in Taiwan."

56
00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:39.800
(IN SOUTHERN ACCENT)
So long. cowboy with the fake Stetson.

57
00:04:39.900 --> 00:04:40.900
Baby. please.

58
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:42.700
(IN NORMAL VOICE) Richard.
I got to go. And seriously...

59
00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:44.600
- What the hell are you doing?
- I'm sorry.

60
00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:49.400
- I'm so sorry. I really need your help.
- Stop! Stop it! Take this off me right now!

61
00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:50.700
- I can't.
- Take this off me right now!

62
00:04:50.800 --> 00:04:52.700
I can't. Mr. Jang's the
only one who has the key.

63
00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:55.000
All you have to do is go into the hotel
and ask for him at the reception.

64
00:04:55.100 --> 00:04:57.800
- No! Take it off me right now!
- I'm so sorry. I really have no choice.

65
00:04:57.900 --> 00:04:59.600
The sooner you go in.
the sooner you'll be back out!

66
00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:03.200
- I can't believe you did this to me.
- I'll be right here. You have my word.

67
00:05:03.300 --> 00:05:08.200
- Your word isn't worth shit!
- It's worth 500 bucks. up front.

68
00:05:08.700 --> 00:05:10.800
- You're an asshole.
- And you're wonderful.

69
00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:11.900
(SCOFFS)

70
00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:33.600
- Miss. may I help you?
- Uh. yes.

71
00:05:35.800 --> 00:05:37.400
I'm here for. uh...

72
00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:39.900
Mr. Jang.

73
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:42.400
Yes. um...

74
00:05:49.100 --> 00:05:50.700
Who should I say is here?

75
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:53.300
Richard.

76
00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:56.600
Um. Richard sent me.

77
00:05:57.600 --> 00:05:59.400
(SPEAKING MANDARIN)

78
00:06:00.900 --> 00:06:02.000
What is your name?

79
00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:04.300
No. Richard.

80
00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:09.300
Richard's... He's just
looking for a place to park.

81
00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:10.800
(CONTINUES SPEAKING MANDARIN)

82
00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:18.400
Mr. Jang still wants
to know your name.

83
00:06:22.300 --> 00:06:24.600
- Lucy.
- Lucy what?

84
00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:29.200
Just Lucy. If he could be quick.
because I have to...

85
00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:31.600
Just a second while I translate.

86
00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:40.100
Mr. Jang is on his way.
Stay right here.

87
00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:42.800
Can I sit?

88
00:06:42.900 --> 00:06:47.300
Mr. Jang said you need to stay right here.
I think it's better if you stay right here.

89
00:06:47.700 --> 00:06:50.800
- (PHONE RINGING)
- Excuse me. Regent Hotel.

90
00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:55.500
(CONCIERGE SPEAKING MANDARIN)

91
00:07:10.600 --> 00:07:12.800
- (GUNSHOTS)
- No!

92
00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:15.500
(SPEAKS MANDARIN)

93
00:07:18.500 --> 00:07:20.100
- (MAN SPEAKS MANDARIN)
- (GASPS)

94
00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:25.600
No!

95
00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:28.900
(LUCY GRUNTING)

96
00:07:32.100 --> 00:07:33.900
(CRYING) Please. Please!

97
00:07:40.800 --> 00:07:43.200
LUCY: Please! I don't know anything!

98
00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:46.600
I don't know anything!
Please! Please!

99
00:07:49.300 --> 00:07:50.700
(LUCY SOBBING)

100
00:08:02.300 --> 00:08:04.100
(MAN SPEAKS KOREAN)

101
00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:09.300
(RETCHING)

102
00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:12.600
(LUCY COUGHS)

103
00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:13.800
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

104
00:08:15.300 --> 00:08:17.800
No! Please!

105
00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:25.600
MAN: Hmm.

106
00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:43.500
(SIGHS)

107
00:08:56.100 --> 00:08:57.200
Do you speak English?

108
00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:04.100
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

109
00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:08.200
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

110
00:09:21.300 --> 00:09:22.500
Lucy! Yes. I'm Lucy.

111
00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.900
This has just been a terrible mistake.
I'm just supposed to deliver this case.

112
00:09:27.800 --> 00:09:29.900
If you lost the key. you don't
have to chop off my hand.

113
00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.100
(VOICE BREAKING)
You can just cut the chain. okay?

114
00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:38.800
Please. I'm begging you. please.

115
00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:40.600
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

116
00:09:40.800 --> 00:09:43.400
No. no. no!

117
00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:45.300
(LUCY STRUGGLING)

118
00:09:49.500 --> 00:09:52.600
(CRYING) Please. Please!

119
00:09:56.700 --> 00:09:58.200
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

120
00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:08.600
TRANSLATOR: Hello. miss. I speak
English. I translate for Mr. Jang.

121
00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:15.500
(INHALES SHARPLY)

122
00:10:16.700 --> 00:10:21.600
Please tell him that I haven't done
anything. I don't know anything.

123
00:10:22.300 --> 00:10:26.300
It's all just a big mistake. okay?
Please tell him that.

124
00:10:26.300 --> 00:10:28.400
Yes. okay. okay. Hold on.

125
00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:30.500
(TRANSLATOR SPEAKING KOREAN)

126
00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:36.700
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

127
00:10:37.100 --> 00:10:39.900
Mr. Jang wants to know
what's in the case.

128
00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.500
No. I don't know what's in the case. Do you
speak English or don't you speak English?

129
00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:47.600
Yes. I do. I studied one year at
International High School in New York.

130
00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:49.100
Okay.

131
00:10:50.300 --> 00:10:53.800
Richard gave me the case to
give to you. that's all I know.

132
00:10:53.900 --> 00:10:55.900
Okay? Please tell him that.

133
00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.200
(TRANSLATOR SPEAKING KOREAN)

134
00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:11.600
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

135
00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:25.600
He gave me a paper with numbers
written on it. What is this?

136
00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:28.100
It's the code to open the case.

137
00:11:34.200 --> 00:11:37.700
- What's really in here?
- Nothing dangerous.

138
00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:41.600
So why won't he open it himself?

139
00:11:41.800 --> 00:11:44.000
(TRANSLATOR SPEAKING KOREAN)

140
00:11:44.200 --> 00:11:45.900
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

141
00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:49.000
He doesn't trust Mr. Richard.

142
00:11:49.100 --> 00:11:53.100
I don't trust Richard. either.
I only dated him for a week.

143
00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:55.100
(TRANSLATOR SPEAKING KOREAN)

144
00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:57.000
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

145
00:11:57.800 --> 00:11:59.100
(SHOUTING)

146
00:11:59.900 --> 00:12:01.500
Okay. okay. okay.

147
00:12:01.600 --> 00:12:04.400
- Mr. Jang insists that you open the case.
- Okay. okay.

148
00:12:09.200 --> 00:12:11.500
(SOBBING) Please. God. help me.

149
00:12:17.900 --> 00:12:19.400
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

150
00:12:20.300 --> 00:12:23.900
He wants you to hurry up.
Mr. Jang has other things to do.

151
00:12:47.500 --> 00:12:48.600
(GASPS)

152
00:12:53.700 --> 00:12:55.300
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

153
00:12:56.200 --> 00:12:58.300
Can you describe the
contents of the case?

154
00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:02.200
It's four plastic pouches filled
with a blue powder. Like a...

155
00:13:02.300 --> 00:13:05.800
Maybe a purple powder.
I don't know. It looks gross.

156
00:13:05.900 --> 00:13:09.000
(TRANSLATOR SPEAKING KOREAN)

157
00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:11.700
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

158
00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:04.800
(MAN SPEAKING KOREAN)

159
00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:27.300
(INHALES)

160
00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:30.600
(COUGHS AND WHEEZES)

161
00:14:37.700 --> 00:14:38.800
(PANTING)

162
00:14:42.300 --> 00:14:43.800
(LAUGHING)

163
00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:53.500
(LAUGHING MANIACALLY)

164
00:14:59.600 --> 00:15:00.600
(GASPS)

165
00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:04.200
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

166
00:15:06.600 --> 00:15:07.800
(GASPING)

167
00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:11.800
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

168
00:15:23.400 --> 00:15:25.500
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

169
00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:28.800
TRANSLATOR:
Mr. Jang wants to offer you a job.

170
00:15:30.300 --> 00:15:31.600
A job?

171
00:15:35.300 --> 00:15:37.300
(CRYING) I don't want a job.

172
00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:42.700
NORMAN: If life starts
approximately a billion years ago.

173
00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:48.500
we will have to wait 400.000 years to see
the aberration of the first nerve cells.

174
00:15:48.800 --> 00:15:51.200
This is where life as
we know it begins.

175
00:15:51.300 --> 00:15:54.500
Brains in formation of
only a few milligrams.

176
00:15:55.100 --> 00:16:00.100
It's not possible to determine
any sign of intelligence yet.

177
00:16:00.200 --> 00:16:02.700
It acts more as a reflex.

178
00:16:02.900 --> 00:16:06.500
One neuron. you're alive.
Two neurons.

179
00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:12.100
you're moving. and with movement.
interesting things begin to happen.

180
00:16:12.400 --> 00:16:13.900
(VARIOUS ANIMALS CRYING OUT)

181
00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:21.100
Animal life on Earth goes
back millions of years.

182
00:16:21.300 --> 00:16:26.500
Yet most species only use 3 to
5% of its cerebral capacity.

183
00:16:26.600 --> 00:16:31.500
But it isn't until we reached human
beings at the top of the animal chain

184
00:16:31.600 --> 00:16:36.300
that we finally see a species use
more of its cerebral capacity.

185
00:16:37.900 --> 00:16:39.000
(GRUNTING)

186
00:16:39.700 --> 00:16:44.000
10% may not seem like much. but it's a
lot if you look at all we've done with it.

187
00:17:15.500 --> 00:17:16.700
(GRUNTING)

188
00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.400
NORMAN:
Now let's discuss a special case.

189
00:17:20.500 --> 00:17:25.600
The only living being that
uses its brain better than us.

190
00:17:26.100 --> 00:17:27.200
The dolphin.

191
00:17:28.500 --> 00:17:31.700
It is estimated that
this incredible animal

192
00:17:31.900 --> 00:17:36.200
uses up to 20% of its
cerebral capacity.

193
00:17:36.300 --> 00:17:39.800
In particular. this allows it

194
00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:42.500
to have an echolocation system

195
00:17:42.600 --> 00:17:47.500
that is more efficient than any
sonar invented by mankind.

196
00:17:47.700 --> 00:17:52.300
But the dolphin did not invent
the sonar. it developed it naturally.

197
00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:59.300
And this is the crucial part of our
philosophical reflection we have today.

198
00:17:59.500 --> 00:18:04.900
Can we therefore conclude that
humans are concerned more with

199
00:18:05.300 --> 00:18:08.900
having... than being?

200
00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:11.900
(SIRENS WAILING IN DISTANCE)

201
00:18:23.100 --> 00:18:24.300
(GROANS)

202
00:18:32.200 --> 00:18:33.600
(PANTING)

203
00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:42.100
(SIGHS)

204
00:18:42.200 --> 00:18:43.300
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

205
00:18:53.600 --> 00:18:54.900
(MELLOW MUSIC PLAYING)

206
00:19:06.200 --> 00:19:08.000
Lucy.

207
00:19:08.100 --> 00:19:10.700
What did you do to my stomach?

208
00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.900
MAN: Nothing! Just a little
(SNIFFLING) horizontal slit.

209
00:19:14.600 --> 00:19:16.500
It's very well done. And...

210
00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.600
You'll find within a month.
the scar is practically invisible.

211
00:19:20.900 --> 00:19:24.200
So. you'll be able to show your
tummy off on the beach next summer.

212
00:19:24.300 --> 00:19:26.300
I don't care about the scar.

213
00:19:27.300 --> 00:19:30.800
(STAMMERING)
Is it why we opened you up. yeah?

214
00:19:32.100 --> 00:19:35.200
Rest assured. we didn't harvest
your organs or anything.

215
00:19:35.300 --> 00:19:38.900
We merely slipped a little
package into your lower tummy.

216
00:19:39.200 --> 00:19:42.800
It's a new drug that kids in Europe
are going to love. believe me.

217
00:19:42.900 --> 00:19:47.100
- What is it?
- Well. the scientific term is C.P.H.4.

218
00:19:47.600 --> 00:19:50.200
Which is not very sexy from
a sales point of view.

219
00:19:50.300 --> 00:19:56.000
So we're still working on something
with a bit more pop. Any suggestions?

220
00:19:57.500 --> 00:19:59.700
Ah! Excuse me.

221
00:20:00.100 --> 00:20:03.500
Welcome! Welcome. come on in.
Lovely! Oops!

222
00:20:06.500 --> 00:20:08.400
Splendid. splendid!

223
00:20:09.200 --> 00:20:10.500
(THE LIMEY LAUGHS)

224
00:20:10.700 --> 00:20:12.100
Marvelous! Lovely. lovely.

225
00:20:12.700 --> 00:20:13.800
Oh!

226
00:20:14.400 --> 00:20:15.800
- How are you?
- MAN: Very good. my dear.

227
00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:17.700
THE LIMEY: Okay.

228
00:20:17.800 --> 00:20:20.400
Right. Um... First of all.

229
00:20:20.700 --> 00:20:23.300
many thanks for taking
part in this enterprise.

230
00:20:23.400 --> 00:20:28.300
which I'm sure will go off flawlessly.
These lovely passports and tickets

231
00:20:28.400 --> 00:20:31.900
will enable you to return
home in the next 24 hours.

232
00:20:32.200 --> 00:20:36.000
Now. upon arrival. you will be
taken in hand by our people.

233
00:20:36.100 --> 00:20:38.500
so that we might recover
our merchandise

234
00:20:38.700 --> 00:20:42.600
and you might rediscover the freedom
which you so richly deserve.

235
00:20:43.200 --> 00:20:47.700
I'm sure I don't need to remind you.
but for any of those who may be tempted

236
00:20:47.800 --> 00:20:51.900
to warn or turn themselves
in to the authorities.

237
00:20:52.800 --> 00:20:57.700
we have the names and addresses of
the families of every one of you.

238
00:20:58.100 --> 00:21:00.700
down to the most
distant cousins. right?

239
00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:01.800
(COUGHS)

240
00:21:01.900 --> 00:21:05.900
So. we rely. therefore.
on your complete discretion.

241
00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.400
Good! (CLEARS THROAT)
Anyway. gentlemen. madam.

242
00:21:09.500 --> 00:21:13.800
allow me to be the first
to wish you... bon voyage!

243
00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:21.100
Oops. (CHUCKLES)

244
00:21:22.300 --> 00:21:23.400
Lovely.

245
00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:27.200
- You're gonna sell this?
- I'm afraid it's our business model.

246
00:21:29.400 --> 00:21:34.800
NORMAN: For primitive beings like us.
life seems to have only one single purpose.

247
00:21:34.900 --> 00:21:36.300
gaining time.

248
00:21:37.200 --> 00:21:40.600
And it is going through
time that seems to be also

249
00:21:40.700 --> 00:21:44.100
the only real purpose of each
of the cells in our bodies.

250
00:21:44.500 --> 00:21:47.300
To achieve that aim.
the mass of the cells

251
00:21:47.400 --> 00:21:52.800
that make up earthworms and human
beings has only two solutions.

252
00:21:53.100 --> 00:21:57.400
Be immortal... or to reproduce.

253
00:21:57.500 --> 00:22:01.800
If its habitat is not sufficiently
favorable or nurturing...

254
00:22:09.200 --> 00:22:11.400
The cell will choose immortality.

255
00:22:11.500 --> 00:22:15.800
In other words. self-sufficiency
and self-management.

256
00:22:16.300 --> 00:22:19.600
On the other hand. if the
habitat is favorable...

257
00:22:24.700 --> 00:22:26.700
They will choose to reproduce.

258
00:22:35.900 --> 00:22:41.100
That way. when they die. they hand down
essential information and knowledge

259
00:22:41.100 --> 00:22:44.500
to the next cell. which hands it
down to the next cell and so on.

260
00:22:56.700 --> 00:23:01.700
Thus. knowledge and learning
are handed down through time.

261
00:23:03.400 --> 00:23:08.200
LUCY: Okay. okay. Keep calm.
You have to wait. Just play for time.

262
00:23:08.300 --> 00:23:11.100
You'll have time to think it through
on the plane. Just take the flight.

263
00:23:11.200 --> 00:23:15.400
Take the flight. get out of here. That's
the main thing right now. Just save time.

264
00:23:15.500 --> 00:23:18.500
Don't try anything.
Keep your cool. You're alive.

265
00:23:18.600 --> 00:23:22.400
You're alive. babe. You're alive.
That's all that matters. Just wait.

266
00:23:22.500 --> 00:23:23.900
Save time.

267
00:23:25.600 --> 00:23:26.700
Save time.

268
00:23:28.600 --> 00:23:30.100
(SPEAKING MANDARIN)

269
00:23:59.300 --> 00:24:00.800
I'm not in the mood.

270
00:24:00.900 --> 00:24:03.500
(MEN SPEAKING MANDARIN)

271
00:24:12.100 --> 00:24:14.200
(MAN GRUNTING)

272
00:24:14.300 --> 00:24:15.600
(LUCY GROANING)

273
00:24:16.400 --> 00:24:18.000
(SHOUTING IN MANDARIN)

274
00:24:19.600 --> 00:24:21.000
(WHIMPERING)

275
00:24:22.900 --> 00:24:24.000
(COUGHS)

276
00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:31.500
(GRUNTING)

277
00:24:54.900 --> 00:24:57.000
(PANTING)

278
00:25:01.400 --> 00:25:03.800
(GROANING)

279
00:25:48.600 --> 00:25:49.700
(SCREAMING)

280
00:25:53.500 --> 00:25:54.600
(PANTING)

281
00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:56.100
(SCREAMING)

282
00:25:58.200 --> 00:26:00.300
NORMAN:
Let's imagine for a few moments

283
00:26:00.400 --> 00:26:04.000
what our life would be like if
we could access. let's say.

284
00:26:04.200 --> 00:26:07.200
20% of our brain's capacity.

285
00:26:07.300 --> 00:26:13.700
This first stage would give us access
to and control of our own body.

286
00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:15.800
- Sir?
- Yes.

287
00:26:16.300 --> 00:26:17.800
Has it been proved scientifically?

288
00:26:17.900 --> 00:26:23.800
For the moment. it's just hypothesis.
I confess. But if you think about it.

289
00:26:23.900 --> 00:26:28.600
it's troubling to realize that the Greeks.
the Egyptians and the Indians

290
00:26:28.700 --> 00:26:33.200
had notion of cells centuries before
the invention of the microscope.

291
00:26:33.600 --> 00:26:35.200
And what to say about Darwin.

292
00:26:35.300 --> 00:26:39.600
whom everybody took for a fool when
he put forth his theory of evolution.

293
00:26:39.700 --> 00:26:43.200
It's up to us to push
the rules and laws

294
00:26:43.400 --> 00:26:46.000
and go from evolution to revolution.

295
00:26:46.400 --> 00:26:47.500
(ALL LAUGH)

296
00:26:48.500 --> 00:26:54.300
100 billion neurons per human.
of which only 15% are activated.

297
00:26:54.400 --> 00:26:59.000
There are more connections in the human
body than there are stars in the galaxy.

298
00:26:59.600 --> 00:27:03.500
We possess a gigantic
network of information

299
00:27:03.600 --> 00:27:06.200
to which we have almost no access.

300
00:27:08.100 --> 00:27:09.300
- Sir?
- Yes.

301
00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:11.200
And what will be the next stage?

302
00:27:11.500 --> 00:27:14.800
Well. the next stage would probably
be control of other people.

303
00:27:15.700 --> 00:27:20.500
But for that. we would need to access
at least 40% of our brain's capacity.

304
00:27:21.300 --> 00:27:26.800
After control of ourselves and
others would come control of matter.

305
00:27:28.200 --> 00:27:31.000
But now we're entering into
the realm of science fiction

306
00:27:31.200 --> 00:27:35.000
and we don't know any more than
a dog who watches the moon.

307
00:27:35.400 --> 00:27:37.100
- Excuse me. sir.
- Yes.

308
00:27:37.300 --> 00:27:40.600
But what would happen if.
for some reason we ignore.

309
00:27:40.700 --> 00:27:44.200
somebody unlocked 100%
of their cerebral capacity?

310
00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:48.400
- 100%?
- Yes.

311
00:27:51.500 --> 00:27:53.200
I have no idea.

312
00:28:17.900 --> 00:28:19.000
(DOOR UNLOCKS)

313
00:29:08.600 --> 00:29:09.700
Ahhh!

314
00:29:19.700 --> 00:29:21.300
(MEN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

315
00:29:25.100 --> 00:29:26.200
Hey!

316
00:30:33.200 --> 00:30:34.700
(SPEAKING MANDARIN)

317
00:30:36.900 --> 00:30:39.000
- Hey! You speak English?
- No. no. no.

318
00:30:39.100 --> 00:30:40.100
Ahhh!

319
00:30:40.200 --> 00:30:41.700
- You speak English?
- Yes. yes.

320
00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:43.700
- Take me to the hospital now.
- Hospital.

321
00:30:44.700 --> 00:30:46.000
(INJURED CABBIE SPEAKING MANDARIN)

322
00:30:46.100 --> 00:30:47.300
My leg!

323
00:31:06.100 --> 00:31:07.700
(SPEAKING MANDARIN)

324
00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:35.300
- Hospital!
- Wait for me.

325
00:32:22.200 --> 00:32:24.000
SURGEON: Miss! Hello?

326
00:32:26.400 --> 00:32:29.700
- Hey! Miss!
- I need help. It's urgent.

327
00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:33.800
You cannot be in here.
We are operating! Please. get out!

328
00:32:38.200 --> 00:32:39.300
(GASPS)

329
00:32:43.400 --> 00:32:44.700
(NURSE SCREAMS)

330
00:32:52.700 --> 00:32:54.900
You wouldn't have been
able to save him anyway.

331
00:32:55.100 --> 00:32:58.100
The tumor had already invaded the
cortex and the right side of his spine.

332
00:33:01.100 --> 00:33:04.700
Somebody put a bag of drugs in me.
I need you to remove it. It's leaking.

333
00:33:07.500 --> 00:33:08.900
Do it now.

334
00:33:09.400 --> 00:33:12.900
Right. I'll just administer
a local anesthetic.

335
00:33:12.900 --> 00:33:14.300
Don't bother.

336
00:33:14.400 --> 00:33:17.700
Right. Okay.

337
00:33:17.900 --> 00:33:21.000
Calm down. please. Put the gun down.

338
00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:25.500
I'm just going to examine. okay?

339
00:33:28.800 --> 00:33:30.600
- Do you mind?
- No.

340
00:33:31.600 --> 00:33:33.000
(DIALING)

341
00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:39.400
(LINE RINGING)

342
00:33:39.600 --> 00:33:41.600
- WOMAN: Hello?
- Mom?

343
00:33:41.700 --> 00:33:43.600
Hey! Lucy.

344
00:33:43.700 --> 00:33:48.600
Baby. it's great to hear from you!
But what time is it over there?

345
00:33:50.200 --> 00:33:51.400
I don't know. it's night.

346
00:33:51.500 --> 00:33:53.500
Hold on a sec. let me
get rid of the other line.

347
00:33:53.600 --> 00:33:55.900
I'm going to have to go inside.

348
00:33:56.700 --> 00:33:59.800
I'm back. You're not
partying too much. are you?

349
00:33:59.900 --> 00:34:02.400
You promised me you'd
look after yourself.

350
00:34:02.500 --> 00:34:05.100
I'm trying to. Mom.
I am trying to.

351
00:34:05.200 --> 00:34:09.100
Well. thanks for calling
out of the blue like this.

352
00:34:09.200 --> 00:34:13.000
Your father's gonna be sad he missed you.
He isn't home from the gym yet.

353
00:34:13.500 --> 00:34:15.800
Usually. you call us in the morning.

354
00:34:15.900 --> 00:34:18.000
- Mom?
- Yes?

355
00:34:18.500 --> 00:34:20.300
I feel everything.

356
00:34:21.100 --> 00:34:23.200
What do you mean. sweetie?

357
00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:26.500
Space.

358
00:34:27.400 --> 00:34:29.100
the air.

359
00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:34.900
the vibrations.

360
00:34:36.400 --> 00:34:38.000
the people.

361
00:34:40.100 --> 00:34:42.500
I can feel the gravity.

362
00:34:43.900 --> 00:34:46.600
I can feel the rotation of the Earth.

363
00:34:48.300 --> 00:34:50.600
the heat leaving my body.

364
00:34:51.800 --> 00:34:53.700
the blood in my veins.

365
00:34:55.400 --> 00:34:57.700
I can feel my brain.

366
00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.700
the deepest parts of my memory...

367
00:35:01.900 --> 00:35:05.700
Sweetie. we have a bad connection.
I can't hear you so well.

368
00:35:05.800 --> 00:35:07.900
What did you say about memory?

369
00:35:09.900 --> 00:35:14.300
The pain in my mouth
when I had braces.

370
00:35:14.400 --> 00:35:19.700
I can remember the feeling of your hand
on my forehead when I ran a fever.

371
00:35:20.800 --> 00:35:23.600
I remember stroking
the cat. it was so soft.

372
00:35:23.700 --> 00:35:26.500
The cat? What cat. honey?

373
00:35:27.500 --> 00:35:30.300
A Siamese with blue
eyes and a broken tail.

374
00:35:30.400 --> 00:35:34.800
Sweetie. you can't possibly remember that.
You were barely a year old.

375
00:35:37.700 --> 00:35:42.100
I remember the taste of
your milk in my mouth.

376
00:35:43.100 --> 00:35:47.200
The room. the liquid...

377
00:35:49.200 --> 00:35:53.100
Sweetie. what are you talking about?

378
00:35:54.600 --> 00:35:58.400
I just wanna tell you that
I love you. Mom and Dad.

379
00:35:58.500 --> 00:35:59.800
Sweetie...

380
00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:06.300
And I wanna thank you for the thousand
kisses that I can still feel on my face.

381
00:36:09.800 --> 00:36:11.600
I love you. Mom.

382
00:36:11.700 --> 00:36:16.700
I love you. too. sweetie.
More than anything in the world.

383
00:36:25.400 --> 00:36:27.200
How much is left?

384
00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:29.800
500 grams.

385
00:36:30.500 --> 00:36:34.400
And how long will it take my body
to eliminate the rest of it?

386
00:36:36.600 --> 00:36:40.400
To answer that. I need to
know what it is. May I?

387
00:36:40.800 --> 00:36:41.900
Go ahead.

388
00:36:43.100 --> 00:36:44.500
C.P.H.4.

389
00:36:48.300 --> 00:36:49.900
Tell me about it.

390
00:36:51.900 --> 00:36:54.100
Pregnant women manufacture C.P.H.4

391
00:36:54.200 --> 00:36:58.200
in the sixth week of pregnancy
in tiny quantities.

392
00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:02.900
For a baby. it packs the
power of an atomic bomb.

393
00:37:03.700 --> 00:37:09.200
It's what gives the fetus the necessary
energy to form all the bones in its body.

394
00:37:09.300 --> 00:37:12.000
I'd heard they tried to make
a synthetic version of it.

395
00:37:12.100 --> 00:37:13.900
I didn't realize that
they'd succeeded.

396
00:37:15.100 --> 00:37:17.200
If it really is C.P.H.4.

397
00:37:17.800 --> 00:37:21.100
in this quantity.
I'm amazed you're still alive.

398
00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:23.600
Not for long.

399
00:37:31.200 --> 00:37:32.300
(SIGHS)

400
00:37:56.800 --> 00:37:59.400
(CLASSICAL MUSIC
PLAYING ON HEADPHONES)

401
00:39:28.900 --> 00:39:29.900
(GROANING)

402
00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:32.800
Learning's always a painful process.

403
00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:36.800
Like when you're little and your bones
are growing and you ache all over.

404
00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:40.700
Can you believe I can remember
the sound of my own bones growing?

405
00:39:42.100 --> 00:39:46.300
Like this grinding under the skin.
Everything's different now.

406
00:39:46.400 --> 00:39:51.000
Like. sounds are music that
I can understand. like fluids.

407
00:39:52.500 --> 00:39:57.900
It's funny. I used to be so concerned
with who I was and what I wanted to be

408
00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:01.900
and now that I have access to
the furthest reaches of my brain.

409
00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:06.500
I see things clearly and realize that
what makes us us it's primitive.

410
00:40:08.200 --> 00:40:12.600
They're all obstacles.
Does that make any sense?

411
00:40:13.300 --> 00:40:18.100
Like this pain you're experiencing.
It's blocking you from understanding.

412
00:40:19.200 --> 00:40:23.100
All you know now is pain.
That's all you know. pain.

413
00:40:26.300 --> 00:40:27.400
Where are the others?

414
00:40:28.300 --> 00:40:33.000
The others carrying the drugs. I need
the rest of it. for medicinal purposes.

415
00:40:34.800 --> 00:40:35.900
(CONTINUES GROANING)

416
00:41:03.200 --> 00:41:04.600
Berlin.

417
00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:10.900
Paris.

418
00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:18.700
Rome.

419
00:41:24.100 --> 00:41:25.800
Thank you for sharing.

420
00:41:27.100 --> 00:41:29.700
(SHUDDERING. SCREAMING)

421
00:41:39.900 --> 00:41:42.600
- Oh. Evening. Professor.
- Bonsoir. Albert.

422
00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:47.100
- Do we have you for dinner tonight?
- I'm afraid so. I'm exhausted.

423
00:41:47.200 --> 00:41:49.400
- Have a good rest.
- Thank you.

424
00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:52.400
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

425
00:41:53.800 --> 00:41:54.800
(SNARLS)

426
00:41:54.900 --> 00:41:58.800
You scared the shit out of me.
ringing that bell like some nutbar!

427
00:41:58.800 --> 00:42:00.200
I missed you.

428
00:42:02.600 --> 00:42:03.800
Me. too.

429
00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:07.900
- Yeah. you lose your keys or something?
- Yeah.

430
00:42:08.800 --> 00:42:11.500
- Can I borrow your laptop?
- Yeah. of course.

431
00:42:11.600 --> 00:42:14.400
So I spent all of yesterday in
auditions. which are awesome.

432
00:42:14.600 --> 00:42:16.400
They just have you
standing around all day

433
00:42:16.500 --> 00:42:19.700
because they don't give a shit about
your time gabbing away in Chinese.

434
00:42:19.800 --> 00:42:22.800
Who understands Chinese?
I don't understand Chinese.

435
00:42:22.900 --> 00:42:25.700
And then they say they're always
gonna call. and they never do.

436
00:42:25.800 --> 00:42:27.800
because they don't even take
your phone number. You know?

437
00:42:27.900 --> 00:42:30.800
Except this one guy.
but he's not Chinese.

438
00:42:31.300 --> 00:42:33.600
He works at the agency and he's cute.

439
00:42:33.700 --> 00:42:37.300
Oh. my God. he's cute. In the
cute-and-I-kinda-know-it kinda way.

440
00:42:37.400 --> 00:42:39.700
Like he had this thing...
Oh. my God. and his ass!

441
00:42:40.100 --> 00:42:42.100
Phew! Let me get started on that!

442
00:42:42.700 --> 00:42:44.800
And you are never gonna
guess where he took me.

443
00:42:45.700 --> 00:42:50.100
BOTH: Four Seasons. Royal Suites.
and we made love all night.

444
00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:54.300
I'm sorry. I'm talking about myself.
What's up? How's Richard?

445
00:42:54.500 --> 00:42:55.700
He's dead.

446
00:42:55.900 --> 00:42:59.600
You guys are crazy.
I'm gonna take a shower.

447
00:43:04.100 --> 00:43:05.200
(PHONE RINGING)

448
00:43:10.600 --> 00:43:13.000
- Yes?
- LUCY: Professor Norman. my name's Lucy.

449
00:43:13.200 --> 00:43:17.200
I just read all your research on
the human brain. We need to meet.

450
00:43:17.300 --> 00:43:18.300
(CHUCKLES)

451
00:43:18.400 --> 00:43:22.800
All of my research?
Well. I'm very flattered. young lady.

452
00:43:22.900 --> 00:43:26.400
but I find that hard to believe.
I must have written no less than...

453
00:43:26.500 --> 00:43:30.900
6.734 pages. I can recite them
to you all by heart. if you wish.

454
00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:37.400
Are you one of Emily's friends?

455
00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:40.300
This sounds like one of her silly jokes.
Is she there with you?

456
00:43:41.100 --> 00:43:42.400
No. I'm all on my own.

457
00:43:44.800 --> 00:43:47.000
- Who are you?
- I just told you.

458
00:43:47.500 --> 00:43:48.600
Uh...

459
00:43:48.800 --> 00:43:52.300
Lucy. right? Yes. sorry.

460
00:43:52.400 --> 00:43:54.900
I read your theory on the
use of the brain's capacity.

461
00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:57.100
It's a little rudimentary.
but you're on the right track.

462
00:43:58.700 --> 00:43:59.900
Thank you.

463
00:44:00.100 --> 00:44:03.200
Professor. my cells are reproducing
at a phenomenal speed.

464
00:44:03.400 --> 00:44:04.800
Several million per second.

465
00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:08.100
I'm having trouble precisely
evaluating the time of my death.

466
00:44:08.200 --> 00:44:12.100
- but I doubt I'll last more than 24 hours.
- What are you talking about?

467
00:44:12.200 --> 00:44:15.500
What I'm saying is that your
theory is not a theory.

468
00:44:15.600 --> 00:44:19.700
I absorbed a large quantity
of synthetic C.P.H.4.

469
00:44:19.800 --> 00:44:23.000
that will allow me to use
100% of my cerebral capacity.

470
00:44:23.200 --> 00:44:26.600
Right now. I'm at 28%.
and what you wrote is true.

471
00:44:26.800 --> 00:44:30.400
Once the brain reaches 20%.
it opens up and expands the rest.

472
00:44:30.500 --> 00:44:33.500
There are no more obstacles.
They fall away like dominoes.

473
00:44:33.600 --> 00:44:35.300
I'm colonizing my own brain.

474
00:44:37.500 --> 00:44:42.400
Well. (CLEARS THROAT)
I don't know what to... say.

475
00:44:43.600 --> 00:44:48.500
It's true. I've been working on
this theory for over 20 years.

476
00:44:48.600 --> 00:44:54.200
but it's only ever been
hypotheses and research ideas.

477
00:44:54.300 --> 00:44:57.100
I never thought anyone would...

478
00:44:58.700 --> 00:45:02.200
- You can control your own metabolism?
- Yes.

479
00:45:02.600 --> 00:45:05.600
And I can start to control
other people's bodies.

480
00:45:05.700 --> 00:45:09.600
Also. I can control magnetic
and electric waves.

481
00:45:09.700 --> 00:45:12.700
Not all of them. just the most basic.

482
00:45:12.900 --> 00:45:16.000
Television. Telephone.

483
00:45:16.100 --> 00:45:17.200
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

484
00:45:17.600 --> 00:45:18.600
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

485
00:45:18.700 --> 00:45:21.100
- Radio.
- (RADIO SWITCHING STATIONS)

486
00:45:23.500 --> 00:45:25.100
That's amazing.

487
00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:28.900
I don't feel pain.

488
00:45:30.300 --> 00:45:33.800
fear. desire.

489
00:45:35.600 --> 00:45:39.200
It's like all things that make
us human are fading away.

490
00:45:40.600 --> 00:45:44.300
It's like the less human I feel.

491
00:45:45.300 --> 00:45:49.100
all this knowledge about everything.

492
00:45:49.200 --> 00:45:52.200
quantum physics. applied mathematics.

493
00:45:53.800 --> 00:45:56.800
the infinite capacity
of a cell's nucleus.

494
00:45:57.200 --> 00:46:01.300
They're all exploding inside
my brain. all this knowledge.

495
00:46:01.400 --> 00:46:03.100
I don't know what to do with it.

496
00:46:05.700 --> 00:46:08.900
If you're asking me what to do...

497
00:46:17.900 --> 00:46:19.300
You know.

498
00:46:21.900 --> 00:46:26.600
if you think about...
the very nature of life.

499
00:46:27.200 --> 00:46:30.000
I mean. from the very beginning.

500
00:46:30.500 --> 00:46:33.700
the development of the first cell

501
00:46:34.700 --> 00:46:37.600
that divided into two cells.

502
00:46:38.900 --> 00:46:41.400
The sole purpose of life has been

503
00:46:42.700 --> 00:46:45.600
to pass on what was learned.

504
00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:49.500
There was no higher purpose.

505
00:46:50.400 --> 00:46:55.400
So if you're asking me what to do with all
this knowledge you're accumulating. I'd say

506
00:46:57.300 --> 00:46:58.800
pass it on.

507
00:47:01.100 --> 00:47:05.200
Just like any simple cell

508
00:47:05.900 --> 00:47:07.500
going through time.

509
00:47:08.900 --> 00:47:10.100
Time.

510
00:47:11.500 --> 00:47:13.000
Yes. of course.

511
00:47:15.600 --> 00:47:17.400
I'll be at your door in 12 hours.

512
00:47:26.200 --> 00:47:28.100
- You're leaving?
- Yes.

513
00:47:31.100 --> 00:47:32.900
- What is this?
- A prescription.

514
00:47:33.700 --> 00:47:35.800
Since when did you start
writing in Chinese?

515
00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:39.100
- Since an hour ago.
- Luce. I don't understand any of this.

516
00:47:39.200 --> 00:47:41.800
Your kidneys aren't functioning
efficiently. your liver's failing you.

517
00:47:41.900 --> 00:47:43.600
You need to make some
lifestyle changes.

518
00:47:43.700 --> 00:47:48.000
Take this medication. work out.
eat organic. You'll be okay.

519
00:47:54.900 --> 00:47:55.900
(SPEAKING MANDARIN)

520
00:47:56.100 --> 00:47:58.400
Last night. at 11 pm.
a woman shot a patient dead.

521
00:47:58.600 --> 00:48:02.800
- It happened at Tri-Service Hospital.
- The suspect is 25. blonde. medium height.

522
00:48:02.900 --> 00:48:07.000
Police are hunting nationwide.
She is armed and dangerous.

523
00:48:21.200 --> 00:48:24.100
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

524
00:48:24.500 --> 00:48:25.600
(ALL LAUGHING)

525
00:48:25.900 --> 00:48:27.100
(PHONE RINGING)

526
00:48:28.500 --> 00:48:29.500
Del Rio.

527
00:48:29.600 --> 00:48:32.400
(IN FRENCH) I've got a weird call
from a US citizen in Taiwan.

528
00:48:32.500 --> 00:48:35.900
A young woman calling to tip
us off about a big drugs ring.

529
00:48:36.100 --> 00:48:38.100
- I'll take it.
- I'll tape you.

530
00:48:38.300 --> 00:48:39.300
DEL RIO: Hello?

531
00:48:39.400 --> 00:48:41.500
I have important information
about a group of drug traffickers.

532
00:48:41.600 --> 00:48:44.000
I need to speak with someone
in a position of authority.

533
00:48:44.100 --> 00:48:48.900
Aha. You're very lucky. there's no one with
more authority in this office than me.

534
00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:51.100
But let's start at the beginning.
What is your name?

535
00:48:51.200 --> 00:48:54.900
Listen up. Pierre Del Rio.
Get off your desk. sit in your chair.

536
00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:57.800
pick up the red pen to the left of
you and take down everything I say.

537
00:49:04.400 --> 00:49:07.700
There are no cameras. Hurry up!
I've no time to waste.

538
00:49:15.500 --> 00:49:16.600
Go ahead.

539
00:49:16.900 --> 00:49:20.100
I'm gonna be sending you the details of
three people about to arrive in Europe.

540
00:49:20.200 --> 00:49:23.100
Each one is carrying a kilo of drugs.
I need you to arrest them

541
00:49:23.200 --> 00:49:25.200
and collect the substance.
I'll need it for later.

542
00:49:25.400 --> 00:49:28.300
What form are these drugs in?
Bars? Capsules?

543
00:49:28.500 --> 00:49:32.200
Powder. Hidden in plastic pouches
inside their intestines.

544
00:49:32.300 --> 00:49:33.300
Excuse me?

545
00:49:33.400 --> 00:49:36.200
Make sure to be careful when you remove
them. The product is very powerful.

546
00:49:36.900 --> 00:49:38.000
(BARKS)

547
00:49:40.100 --> 00:49:41.200
(WHIMPERING)

548
00:49:43.300 --> 00:49:44.400
Believe me.

549
00:49:44.500 --> 00:49:45.600
(COMPUTER BEEPING)

550
00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:48.400
- Got it?
- Yeah.

551
00:49:48.900 --> 00:49:50.100
Good.

552
00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:52.500
I'm counting on you.

553
00:49:54.700 --> 00:49:55.700
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

554
00:49:55.800 --> 00:49:56.900
Okay?

555
00:50:05.700 --> 00:50:06.700
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

556
00:50:06.800 --> 00:50:07.900
Good morning.

557
00:50:10.100 --> 00:50:11.300
Thank you.

558
00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:20.700
That's him! Pick him up.

559
00:50:29.700 --> 00:50:31.400
Come with me. please.

560
00:50:50.800 --> 00:50:52.300
(IN FRENCH) Hello.

561
00:50:52.800 --> 00:50:54.900
Sir. come with us.

562
00:51:10.600 --> 00:51:12.700
(IN ITALIAN) Welcome to Rome.

563
00:51:20.700 --> 00:51:22.200
Good morning. sir.

564
00:51:22.300 --> 00:51:26.200
- Please. follow me. This way.
- Yeah. sure.

565
00:51:29.500 --> 00:51:31.100
(OFFICERS SHOUTING)

566
00:51:31.200 --> 00:51:32.400
(PEOPLE GASPING)

567
00:51:40.400 --> 00:51:41.700
(PHONE RINGING)

568
00:51:43.400 --> 00:51:44.400
Del Rio.

569
00:51:44.500 --> 00:51:47.500
- (SPEAKING ITALIAN)
- Thanks for calling me back.

570
00:51:47.600 --> 00:51:49.000
We took delivery of your package.

571
00:51:49.700 --> 00:51:52.000
Thanks very much. I'll send you
the paperwork for the transfer.

572
00:51:52.100 --> 00:51:53.300
Bye.

573
00:51:53.800 --> 00:51:55.900
(IN FRENCH) Okay. we got all three.

574
00:52:00.100 --> 00:52:01.700
- (BEEPING)
- WOMAN ON PA: Ladies and gentlemen.

575
00:52:01.800 --> 00:52:04.100
we are now beginning our descent
to Paris Charles de Gaulle.

576
00:52:04.300 --> 00:52:05.700
(TYPING RAPIDLY ON KEYBOARD)

577
00:52:13.500 --> 00:52:15.900
Miss. I have to ask you to
put away your computers now.

578
00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:17.200
You should wipe your nose.

579
00:52:17.800 --> 00:52:20.100
- Excuse me?
- May I have a glass of champagne?

580
00:52:22.100 --> 00:52:23.700
Um. yes. Of course.

581
00:52:27.200 --> 00:52:29.100
Could you bring some champagne
to the girl over there?

582
00:52:29.200 --> 00:52:30.300
Yeah. I just have a nosebleed.

583
00:52:42.500 --> 00:52:44.400
Miss. your champagne.

584
00:52:45.600 --> 00:52:46.900
Thank you.

585
00:52:47.300 --> 00:52:50.600
I'm very sorry. but you really
need to close your table now.

586
00:52:51.500 --> 00:52:52.700
Sure.

587
00:53:02.600 --> 00:53:04.100
To knowledge.

588
00:53:14.900 --> 00:53:18.200
If the habitat is not sufficiently
favorable or nurturing...

589
00:53:19.900 --> 00:53:21.000
(COUGHING)

590
00:53:27.700 --> 00:53:29.400
The cell will choose immortality.

591
00:53:35.500 --> 00:53:38.800
In other words. self-sufficiency
and self-management.

592
00:53:45.100 --> 00:53:46.200
(GRUNTS)

593
00:53:54.800 --> 00:53:56.000
No! Miss. miss!

594
00:53:58.200 --> 00:53:59.600
You must remain seated!

595
00:54:00.200 --> 00:54:01.200
Miss!

596
00:54:01.300 --> 00:54:02.400
(SCREAMS)

597
00:54:06.700 --> 00:54:11.900
MAN: Miss! Open the door!
You really have to go back to your seat!

598
00:54:13.300 --> 00:54:15.200
We're gonna land soon.
Please! Open the door.

599
00:54:17.100 --> 00:54:20.200
Please. say something.
Are you okay? Miss?

600
00:54:22.400 --> 00:54:23.700
Miss?

601
00:54:24.800 --> 00:54:26.700
Miss. please. open the door!

602
00:54:30.800 --> 00:54:33.200
Please do something. help me! Please!

603
00:54:43.300 --> 00:54:44.500
We're gonna land soon!
Open the door!

604
00:54:53.900 --> 00:54:57.600
- (LUCY GROANING)
- Miss! Are you okay? Say something!

605
00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:07.200
(IN FRENCH)
With a scar on her lower abdomen?

606
00:55:07.300 --> 00:55:09.000
Pretty recent. with thread in it.

607
00:55:09.500 --> 00:55:11.700
- How is she?
- Fine. She's sleeping.

608
00:55:11.800 --> 00:55:14.500
With the shot I gave her.
she'll be out all day.

609
00:55:24.800 --> 00:55:26.400
(MACHINE BEEPING)

610
00:55:28.600 --> 00:55:29.700
(GROANS)

611
00:55:31.600 --> 00:55:32.800
(BONES CRACK)

612
00:55:48.100 --> 00:55:50.200
(MACHINE BEEPING RAPIDLY)

613
00:55:50.500 --> 00:55:52.100
(BEEPING SLOWS)

614
00:55:57.000 --> 00:55:59.500
- (IN FRENCH) She's awake!
- Are you sure?

615
00:55:59.500 --> 00:56:01.200
She's sitting on the bed.

616
00:56:06.100 --> 00:56:07.200
That's her.

617
00:56:07.300 --> 00:56:09.400
- You didn't restrain her?
- Sure. we did!

618
00:56:10.600 --> 00:56:13.400
Miss! Don't move.

619
00:56:13.500 --> 00:56:15.000
I need to talk to you alone.

620
00:56:15.200 --> 00:56:17.200
And I need you to put
your hands up. please.

621
00:56:38.200 --> 00:56:39.800
Did you get the packets?

622
00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:42.100
Yes.

623
00:56:43.200 --> 00:56:45.900
- Where are they?
- They're safe.

624
00:56:46.500 --> 00:56:50.800
- Here. in Paris.
- They'll be safer in my hands.

625
00:57:09.100 --> 00:57:10.900
(IN FRENCH)
Don't leave the car there. Park it up.

626
00:57:13.100 --> 00:57:14.700
(CELL PHONE BEEPS)

627
00:57:19.600 --> 00:57:22.500
You know. as a cop you
see some pretty weird shit.

628
00:57:22.600 --> 00:57:27.200
But I have to be honest with you. What
you did back there. that freaked me out.

629
00:57:27.700 --> 00:57:32.100
To put everyone to sleep like that.
Do I need to be worried?

630
00:57:32.300 --> 00:57:33.500
No.

631
00:57:34.800 --> 00:57:36.100
Good.

632
00:57:39.800 --> 00:57:42.000
(INDISTINCT VOICES CHATTERING)

633
00:57:50.400 --> 00:57:52.200
(MAN'S VOICE GROWS LOUDER)

634
00:57:57.500 --> 00:57:59.000
Do you mind?

635
00:57:59.300 --> 00:58:00.400
No.

636
00:58:03.200 --> 00:58:05.700
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

637
00:58:18.200 --> 00:58:21.400
- What's that?
- Korean. I'm gonna drive.

638
00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:24.400
Hey! No. no. no.
This is a police car!

639
00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:29.200
You can't. No. this is not possible.
lady. This is a police car.

640
00:58:31.600 --> 00:58:32.900
Okay. okay.

641
00:58:39.900 --> 00:58:40.900
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

642
00:58:41.000 --> 00:58:42.100
Let's go. guys!

643
00:58:46.600 --> 00:58:50.000
Sir. sir. excuse me. sir.
I need to talk to somebody.

644
00:58:50.100 --> 00:58:52.300
(IN FRENCH) Talk to the police.

645
00:58:52.500 --> 00:58:54.900
Look. I'm a German citizen
and I demand to see a lawyer.

646
00:58:55.400 --> 00:58:56.800
(IN FRENCH) I'll check with Surgery.

647
00:58:56.900 --> 00:58:59.300
- Grab us some food.
- You're a foodaholic.

648
00:59:26.000 --> 00:59:27.500
(TIRES SCREECHING)

649
00:59:27.600 --> 00:59:30.300
- Do you always drive like that?
- I've never driven before.

650
00:59:30.700 --> 00:59:31.800
Great.

651
00:59:37.600 --> 00:59:39.700
- Hey. that's one-way.
- We're late.

652
01:00:02.100 --> 01:00:04.900
- Hey. I'd rather be late than dead.
- We never really die.

653
01:00:54.700 --> 01:00:57.600
Sorry. sir. I don't feel good.

654
01:00:58.000 --> 01:00:59.100
(MAN GRUNTS)

655
01:01:00.600 --> 01:01:01.700
(PANTING)

656
01:01:04.700 --> 01:01:07.300
I'm fine. I'm fine.

657
01:01:11.800 --> 01:01:13.100
(CARS HONKING)

658
01:01:15.500 --> 01:01:17.000
(SIRENS WAILING)

659
01:01:19.500 --> 01:01:22.100
- I'm gonna tell them to stop following us.
- Don't bother.

660
01:01:27.100 --> 01:01:28.900
(BEEPING)

661
01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:06.100
(IN FRENCH) I got you bacon...

662
01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:25.600
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

663
01:02:44.700 --> 01:02:46.900
- Give me the case.
- (LAUGHS)

664
01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:49.300
(IN KOREAN)
Kill her and get the pouch.

665
01:02:56.100 --> 01:02:57.200
(GRUNTS)

666
01:03:01.400 --> 01:03:02.500
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

667
01:03:06.600 --> 01:03:08.700
Don't stand there. kill her!

668
01:03:33.400 --> 01:03:34.500
Ahhh!

669
01:03:43.300 --> 01:03:44.400
(GROANING)

670
01:03:56.500 --> 01:03:57.700
Open it.

671
01:04:02.400 --> 01:04:03.800
(SQUELCHING)

672
01:04:11.300 --> 01:04:12.500
Let's go.

673
01:04:12.700 --> 01:04:15.100
I'm not sure I could be
of any help for you.

674
01:04:19.800 --> 01:04:20.900
Yes. you are.

675
01:04:21.800 --> 01:04:23.200
What for?

676
01:04:29.500 --> 01:04:31.000
A reminder.

677
01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:33.500
Shall we go?

678
01:04:52.800 --> 01:04:54.500
(PEOPLE CLAMORING)

679
01:05:01.100 --> 01:05:02.200
Where are we going?

680
01:05:02.700 --> 01:05:04.900
ELECTRONIC VOICE:
Take the first left.

681
01:05:06.500 --> 01:05:07.700
Okay.

682
01:05:17.600 --> 01:05:19.800
(OFFICER IN FRENCH) Move!

683
01:05:23.600 --> 01:05:25.300
(IN KOREAN) Follow that car.

684
01:05:28.800 --> 01:05:30.000
- (CELL PHONE RINGING)
- Professor?

685
01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:32.500
- Hello?
- Lucy.

686
01:05:32.600 --> 01:05:36.200
Oh! It's her! It's her! Hey. you.

687
01:05:36.500 --> 01:05:38.300
- You're in Paris?
- Yes. I am.

688
01:05:38.400 --> 01:05:40.100
Good. good! Excellent.

689
01:05:40.300 --> 01:05:43.600
So. look. I am no longer
at the hotel now.

690
01:05:43.700 --> 01:05:46.700
I have come to the university.
where I've taken the liberty

691
01:05:46.800 --> 01:05:49.800
of calling together a few of my
colleagues to discuss your case.

692
01:05:49.900 --> 01:05:53.000
Top minds in their field
and very trustworthy.

693
01:05:53.100 --> 01:05:55.600
- I trust you.
- Oh. thank you.

694
01:05:55.700 --> 01:05:56.900
So. do you think you could meet us

695
01:05:57.000 --> 01:05:59.200
- here at the university?
- (LINE DISCONNECTS)

696
01:06:02.700 --> 01:06:04.100
I'm. uh...

697
01:06:04.700 --> 01:06:07.300
- I'm very pleased to meet you.
- Likewise.

698
01:06:07.700 --> 01:06:10.500
- Captain Del Rio.
- How do you do?

699
01:06:10.600 --> 01:06:11.700
Um...

700
01:06:11.900 --> 01:06:14.900
Let me introduce you
to my colleagues.

701
01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:19.700
- This is Professor Cartier. neurosurgeon.
- I know who everyone is.

702
01:06:20.900 --> 01:06:22.300
Of course.

703
01:06:22.600 --> 01:06:28.600
Gentlemen. this is Lucy.
the first woman to... I mean...

704
01:06:28.600 --> 01:06:34.100
As I mentioned earlier. Miss Lucy has.
for reasons that remain a mystery to me.

705
01:06:34.200 --> 01:06:37.800
unlocked certain
portions of her brain

706
01:06:37.900 --> 01:06:43.600
that offer access to previously
unexplored cerebral zones.

707
01:06:44.300 --> 01:06:46.600
She has abilities.

708
01:06:47.200 --> 01:06:48.600
Can you give us an example?

709
01:06:49.100 --> 01:06:52.000
Your daughter. Gabrielle.
age six. died in a car accident.

710
01:06:52.600 --> 01:06:57.100
It was a blue car. leather seats. plastic
bird hanging from the rear view mirror.

711
01:06:57.600 --> 01:06:58.700
(SOBBING)

712
01:07:14.000 --> 01:07:16.800
(IN KOREAN) Boss. 5 men
down at the hospital. Sorry.

713
01:07:17.700 --> 01:07:21.800
- How many men left?
- I have about 25 with me.

714
01:07:22.200 --> 01:07:26.400
That damn girl. she doesn't
give in. She's a witch.

715
01:07:28.700 --> 01:07:30.200
I know that.

716
01:07:31.500 --> 01:07:33.700
I'll kill her myself.

717
01:07:38.600 --> 01:07:41.500
There are men coming here. Can you
secure the room? I need to stay focused.

718
01:07:41.600 --> 01:07:42.700
Sure.

719
01:07:46.400 --> 01:07:47.300
(SIRENS WAILING)

720
01:07:48.500 --> 01:07:49.600
(IN KOREAN) Speed it up.

721
01:07:52.400 --> 01:07:53.700
(OFFICERS SHOUTING)

722
01:07:59.800 --> 01:08:02.100
How did you manage to
access all this information?

723
01:08:02.200 --> 01:08:06.800
Electrical impulses. Every cell
knows and talks to every other cell.

724
01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:10.300
They exchange a thousand bits of
information between them per second.

725
01:08:10.400 --> 01:08:13.900
Cells group together.
forming a giant web of communication.

726
01:08:13.900 --> 01:08:15.400
which in turn forms matter.

727
01:08:16.600 --> 01:08:19.400
Cells get together. take on one form.

728
01:08:20.200 --> 01:08:24.600
deform. reform. Makes no difference.
it's all the same.

729
01:08:25.100 --> 01:08:28.500
Humans consider themselves unique.
so they've rooted their whole theory

730
01:08:28.600 --> 01:08:32.600
of existence on their uniqueness.
"One" is their unit of measure.

731
01:08:32.700 --> 01:08:37.200
But it's not. All social systems we've
put into place are a mere sketch.

732
01:08:37.300 --> 01:08:39.800
One plus one equals two.
That's all we've learned.

733
01:08:39.900 --> 01:08:43.000
But one plus one has
never equaled two.

734
01:08:43.100 --> 01:08:46.000
There are. in fact.
no numbers and no letters.

735
01:08:46.100 --> 01:08:49.700
We've codified our existence
to bring it down to human size

736
01:08:49.800 --> 01:08:51.800
to make it comprehensible.

737
01:08:51.900 --> 01:08:56.600
We've created a scale so that we
can forget its unfathomable scale.

738
01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:02.300
But if humans are not
the unit of measure

739
01:09:02.700 --> 01:09:05.500
and the world isn't governed
by mathematical laws.

740
01:09:06.700 --> 01:09:08.000
what governs all that?

741
01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:14.600
Film a car speeding down a road.
Speed up the image infinitely

742
01:09:15.300 --> 01:09:17.300
and the car disappears.

743
01:09:20.200 --> 01:09:23.200
So what proof do we
have of its existence?

744
01:09:23.500 --> 01:09:29.000
Time gives legitimacy to its existence.
Time is the only true unit of measure.

745
01:09:29.400 --> 01:09:32.300
It gives proof to the
existence of matter.

746
01:09:32.700 --> 01:09:34.300
Without time.

747
01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:36.600
we don't exist.

748
01:09:43.300 --> 01:09:44.400
Time is unity.

749
01:09:44.500 --> 01:09:46.200
(ALARMS BLARING)

750
01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:55.700
(IN KOREAN) Search the whole
building and find her!

751
01:09:58.800 --> 01:10:00.800
We won't be able to hold
them for much longer.

752
01:10:02.100 --> 01:10:03.800
Time to go then.

753
01:10:16.800 --> 01:10:21.200
Are you sure you need such huge doses?
I'm afraid you won't survive.

754
01:10:21.300 --> 01:10:25.300
Some cells inside me will fight and
defend their integrity till the very end.

755
01:10:25.500 --> 01:10:29.200
In order to attain the last
few percent. I have to force it

756
01:10:29.300 --> 01:10:31.600
to crack the cells
open to their nucleus.

757
01:10:32.400 --> 01:10:33.500
(SIGHS)

758
01:10:40.700 --> 01:10:43.100
But all of this knowledge. Lucy...

759
01:10:44.900 --> 01:10:47.600
I'm not even sure that
mankind is ready for it.

760
01:10:47.800 --> 01:10:50.600
We're so driven by power and profit.

761
01:10:50.900 --> 01:10:53.100
Given man's nature.

762
01:10:53.800 --> 01:10:57.200
it might bring us only
instability and chaos.

763
01:11:01.300 --> 01:11:03.800
Ignorance brings chaos.
not knowledge.

764
01:11:04.000 --> 01:11:07.100
I'll build a computer and
download all my knowledge in it.

765
01:11:07.200 --> 01:11:10.300
I'll find a way for you
to have access to it.

766
01:11:10.600 --> 01:11:11.800
Yeah.

767
01:11:12.500 --> 01:11:15.800
I just hope we will be
worthy of your sacrifice.

768
01:11:26.000 --> 01:11:27.400
Nobody move!

769
01:11:37.200 --> 01:11:38.700
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

770
01:11:44.500 --> 01:11:46.700
Do you understand English?

771
01:12:09.800 --> 01:12:10.900
(GUNFIRE)

772
01:12:11.500 --> 01:12:12.600
(GASPING)

773
01:12:48.700 --> 01:12:50.000
PROFESSOR: What is she doing?

774
01:12:50.100 --> 01:12:52.600
NORMAN:
She's looking for energy and matter.

775
01:12:56.800 --> 01:13:00.200
And she's trying to connect
with our computers.

776
01:13:40.300 --> 01:13:42.600
- (IN KOREAN) Chong-Ju!
- I'm here. boss.

777
01:13:43.000 --> 01:13:46.400
- Do something about them.
- Okay. boss!

778
01:13:47.900 --> 01:13:49.000
You guys. come on.

779
01:13:50.800 --> 01:13:51.900
Ready?

780
01:13:53.700 --> 01:13:54.800
(IN FRENCH) You okay?

781
01:13:57.000 --> 01:13:58.700
Get a medic. Fast!

782
01:14:03.300 --> 01:14:05.100
PROFESSOR 1:
Oh. my God. What's happening?

783
01:14:15.800 --> 01:14:20.200
- PROFESSOR 2: What is she making?
- New generation computer. I presume.

784
01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:01.200
(SHOUTING IN FRENCH)

785
01:15:08.700 --> 01:15:10.200
(INDISTINCT VOICES CHATTERING)

786
01:16:28.100 --> 01:16:29.600
(TROLLEY BELL RINGING)

787
01:16:33.200 --> 01:16:34.500
(HORSE NEIGHING)

788
01:17:08.000 --> 01:17:09.400
(DISTANT SCREECHING)

789
01:17:13.900 --> 01:17:15.000
(GRUNTING)

790
01:17:20.800 --> 01:17:21.900
(ROARING)

791
01:17:24.600 --> 01:17:26.300
(HUFFING)

792
01:17:35.500 --> 01:17:36.600
(SNARLS)

793
01:17:36.700 --> 01:17:37.800
(HUFFING)

794
01:20:39.400 --> 01:20:40.500
(IN KOREAN) Where is she?

795
01:20:44.700 --> 01:20:47.700
Where is she? Answer me.

796
01:20:48.500 --> 01:20:49.900
Answer me!

797
01:20:50.000 --> 01:20:51.400
Hey. you!

798
01:21:03.900 --> 01:21:05.700
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

799
01:21:08.100 --> 01:21:10.600
PROFESSOR:
Look. The computer. it's moving.

800
01:21:37.000 --> 01:21:40.300
DEL RIO: Hey. Where is she?

801
01:21:43.000 --> 01:21:44.300
(CELL PHONE BEEPS)

802
01:22:09.400 --> 01:22:12.900
LUCY: Life was given to
us a billion years ago.

803
01:22:13.000 --> 01:22:15.500
Now you know what to do with it.

804
